==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hymn
<hw>Hymn</hw> <pr>(h⟦icr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hympne</ets>, <ets>ympne</ets>, F. <ets>hymne</ets>, OF. also
<ets>ymne</ets>, L. <ets>hymnus</ets>, Gr. <?/; perh. akin to <?/ web,
<?/ to weave, and so to E. <ets>weave</ets>.]</ety> <def>An ode or song
of praise or adoration; especially, a religious ode, a sacred lyric; a
song of praise or thanksgiving intended to be used in religious service;
<as>as, the Homeric <ex>hymns</ex>; Watts'
<ex>hymns</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Admonishing one another in psalms and <qex>hymns</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Col. iii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where angels first should practice <qex>hymns</qex>, and
string⟦br⟧
Their tuneful harps.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hymn book</b></col>, <cd>a book containing a collection
of hymns, as for use in churches; a hymnal.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hymn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hymn
<hw>Hymn</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hymned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hymning</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. L.
<ets>hymnire</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>To praise in song; to worship
or extol by singing hymns; to sing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>hymn</qex> the bright of the Lord.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their praise is <qex>hymned</qex> by loftier harps than mine.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hymn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hymn
<hw>Hymn</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To sing in praise or
adoration.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hymnal</ent>⟦br⟧
